Title = {{Language intervention in French-English bilingual aphasia: Evidence of
   limited therapy transfer}},
Journal = {{JOURNAL OF NEUROLINGUISTICS}},
Year = {{2012}},
Volume = {{25}},
Number = {{6, SI}},
Pages = {{588-614}},
Month = {{NOV}},
Abstract = {{This study investigated the effect of treatment in the second language
   (12) for a previously proficient French-English bilingual with aphasia,
   at 5 years post-stroke. Assessment on the Bilingual Aphasia Test (BAT)
   enabled objective measurement of language skills in each language, and
   comparison across languages, before and after treatment in 12 (English).
   Previous therapy had been provided exclusively in L1 (French).
   Pre-treatment assessment on the BAT revealed greater impairment in L2
   than L1, indicating differential recovery and limited transfer from
   previous L1 intervention. Following treatment, re-assessment on the BAT
   in French and English showed significant gains in spoken expression and
   syntactic comprehension in L2 but not L1. Translation in both directions
   was unchanged. Gains in 12 did not exceed L1 pre-treatment scores. These
   results demonstrate language-specific improvement following treatment in
   12, and indicate caution in assuming therapy transfer will occur in
   proficient, highly motivated late bilinguals. The use of the BAT as a
   cross-linguistically valid assessment tool is recommended for future
   bilingual aphasia research. (C) 2011 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.}},
