Number = {{3}},
Pages = {{245-272}},
Month = {{SEP}},
Abstract = {{Functional neuroimaging is charged with revealing thoughts and
   intentions, the source of mental dysfunction, and the basis of
   fundamental human traits. Critics have argued that situating the mind in
   a brain scan risks essentializing contested social and psychiatric
   categories, encourages deterministic perspectives, and diverts attention
   from non-biological ways of understanding the mind. Here, I review these
   critical discourses and ask whether they are reflected in popular media,
   through a discourse analysis of print and online reports of functional
   neuroimaging research deriving primarily from the United Kingdom. In
   contrast to earlier studies, I found diverse challenges to the expertise
   of the scanner, ranging from explicit polemic to assertions of lay
   expertise. Brain images themselves were often manipulated, mislabelled
   or omitted in favour of photographic representations of mental function,
   posing new questions about the rhetorical power of the scan. These
   findings caution against premature conclusions concerning the reductive
   impact of popularized neuroimages, but I also argue for caution
   regarding the reach and novelty of the critical engagements I observed.
   Finally, I argue that qualitative analysis of media texts is essential
   to understanding the developing discourse surrounding functional
   neuroimaging, and discuss possible implications for science
   communication and public engagement practice. BioSocieties (2012) 7,
   245-272. doi:10.1057/biosoc.2012.21; published online 3 September 2012}},
