Title = {{Engagement of amygdala in third-person view of face-to-face interaction}},
Journal = {{HUMAN BRAIN MAPPING}},
Year = {{2012}},
Volume = {{33}},
Number = {{8}},
Pages = {{1753-1762}},
Month = {{AUG}},
Abstract = {{Humans often watch interactions between other people without taking part
   in the interaction themselves. Strikingly little is, however, known
   about how gestures and expressions of two interacting humans are
   processed in the observer's brain, since the study of social cues has
   mostly focused on the perception of solitary humans. To investigate the
   neural underpinnings of the third-person view of social interaction, we
   studied brain activations of subjects who observed two humans either
   facing toward or away from each other. Activations within the amygdala,
   posterior superior temporal sulcus (pSTS), and dorsomedial prefrontal
   cortex (dmPFC) were sensitive to the interactional position of the
   observed people and distinguished humans facing toward from humans
   facing away. The amygdala was most sensitive to face-to-face interaction
   and did not differentiate the humans facing away from the pixelated
   control figures, whereas the pSTS dissociated both human stimuli from
   the pixel figures. The results of the amygdala reactivity suggest that,
   in addition to regulating interpersonal distance towards oneself, the
   amygdala is involved in the assessment of the proximity between two
   other persons. Hum Brain Mapp, 2012. (c) 2011 Wiley Periodicals, Inc.}},
