Abstract = {{The present study aimed to uncover the neural activity associated with
   specific in-group and out-group word related stimuli, to examine the
   neuroanatomical basis of group membership concept representation, and
   investigate to what extent neural processes represent `in-group'
   differently from `out-group'. Participants' brain activity was measured
   with functional MRI while they had to categorize social, in-group and
   out-group words and non-social, living and non-living words. The results
   showed that a network of brain regions previously identified as the
   `social brain', including the cortical midline structures,
   tempo-parietal junction and the anterior temporal gyrus showed enhanced
   activation for social words versus non-social words. Crucially, the
   processing of in-group words compared to the out-group words activated a
   specific network including the ventral medial prefrontal and anterior
   and dorsal cingulate cortex. These regions correspond to a neural
   network previously identified as the `personal self'. Our results
   suggest that the `social' and `personal self are closely related and
   that we derive our self image from the groups we belong to. Crown
