Pages = {{357-364}},
Month = {{MAR}},
Abstract = {{Using fMRI, the present study compares the brain activation underlying
   false belief thinking induced by pictorial, nonverbal material to that
   instigated by strong non-factive verbs in a sample of adult Chinese
   speakers. These verbs obligatorily negate their complements which
   describe the mind content of the sentence agent, and thus may activate
   part of the false belief network. Some previous studies have shown a
   behavioral correlation between verb non-factivity/false complementation
   and conventional false belief but corresponding neural evidence is
   lacking. Our results showed that the non-factive grammar and false
   belief commonly implicated the right temporo-parietal junction (TPJ),
   which had been shown by past studies to play a role in general
   mentalizing. Regions that were unique to nonverbal false belief were the
   left TPJ and right middle frontal gyrus (MFG), whereas the unique
   regions for the non-factive grammar were the left inferior frontal gyrus
   (IFG) and right superior temporal gyrus (STG). Hence, conventional
   nonverbal false belief and verb non-factivity have both shared and
   unique neural representations. (C) 2011 Elsevier B.V. All rights
